        <
        
          ω
          
            2
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \alpha <\omega _{2}}
  , and whose outputs are 
  
    
      
        0
      
    
    {\displaystyle 0}
   or 
  
    
      
        1
      
    
    {\displaystyle 1}
  , one gets 
  
    
      
        
          ω
          
            2
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \omega _{2}}
   new subsets of 
  
    
      
        ω
      
    
    {\displaystyle \omega }
  . They are all distinct, by a density argument: Given 
  
    
      
        α
        <
        β
        <
        
          ω
          
            2
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \alpha <\beta <\omega _{2}}
  , let 

  
    
      
        
          D
          
            α
            ,
            β
          
        
        =
        {
        p
        ∣
        (
        ∃
        n
        )
        (
        p
        (
